##Why Iran is the worst affected region in the Middle East, and how can they fight it effectively?

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

While most people are in a stable mood, pharmacies are running out of face masks, alcohol and disinfectant. Iran, which has been under sanctions for a long time, is indeed unable to cope with the rising demand for medical supplies and medical conditions caused by the outbreak.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A worker takes the temperature of a passenger at the Al Najaf International Airport in Iran on February 21,2020. Figure / Fachen

By Mo Fu, Caijing contributing author, Tehran

Editor | Hao Zhou

In just a few days, a full-blown outbreak of the new coronavirus in Iran has become the fourth-most-affected country in the world, with the world's highest fatality rate, less than a week after the first confirmed case was found, even the Deputy Minister of Health, who is mainly responsible for combating the epidemic, has been diagnosed with the infection. What happened in Iran?

On February 19,28 days after the blockade of Wuhan, Hubei Province, China, in Foshan, Iran reported its first two confirmed cases of pneumonia, or death. In the following days, the number of confirmed cases increased in a straight line, with 3 cases added on the 20th, 13 on the 21st, 10 on the 22nd, 15 on the 23rd, 18 on the 24th, 34 on the 25th and 44 on the 26th. As of February 27 local time, Iran, a total of 141 confirmed cases, 22 deaths.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Iran has the highest number of deaths outside of China, ahead of South Korea (12) and Italy (12) , where the number of confirmed cases is one-tenth that of South Korea. Based on the number of deaths as a percentage of confirmed cases, the fatality rate of the epidemic in Iran is 13.7 per cent, far exceeding that of the concentrated and severe Hubei Province of China, which currently has a fatality rate of about 4 per cent.

Exactly how the virus got to Iran remains a mystery. According to the information already disclosed, Iran's Shi'ite holy city of Qom should be the source of infection and a hard-hit area. About two hours'drive from Tehran, the city's Qom Hawza is one of the world's most prestigious religious schools, and the mausoleum of Fatimah Zahra Masouma is considered one of the holiest places for Shia Islam.

According to an official Iranian survey, the first confirmed cases were found in Qom Qom, who had the most confirmed cases, and most of the other confirmed cases had Qom's travel history. In an interview with the media, the Iranian health minister, Nuri Namaki, concluded that "there is more than a 90 percent chance that the virus was introduced from China to Iran, especially the city of Qom. ". But who exactly carried it in, the workers, the students, the merchants, the travelers in Qom? There's no exact answer.

One of Qom's deaths, Namaki said, was that of an Iranian businessman who had traveled to China during the outbreak. It is also possible that the Iranian businessman was infected with the virus in China and brought back to Iran. So, did the virus originate in China? By what route did it get into Iran? Did the virus mutate in Iran to cause a high fatality rate? There are no definitive answers to these questions.

In addition to the high fatality rate, the epidemic in Iran has also shown itself to be very egalitarian. On February 25, Iran's Deputy Minister of Health, Ali Kharezi, also announced that he had been diagnosed with new coronavirus pneumonia, iran's most senior official has been confirmed with the new coronavirus, which, according to Harazi, is "neither high nor low. ". Iran's presidential spokesman, Rabi Iran, had spent a lot of time with Harazi at the same press conference. Both President Rohani and Rabi were tested for the virus immediately after news of the diagnosis, sources said, but both tested negative on Feb. 26. In addition, the district chief of Tehran's thirteen districts and a member of the national parliament, Sadji, were also diagnosed with the infection.

"It's up to Allah if you get sick. "

After the outbreak, schools in 10 provinces were closed, national sports events, concerts and art exhibitions were canceled, and all cinemas and public leisure venues were closed, tehran has also banned large gatherings such as weddings in public places, Shiraz has closed popular attractions such as the pink mosque, and Gullah province has banned visits by relatives of patients, the public transportation such as each city public transportation, subway also requests the regular disinfection.

After much discussion, Iran has announced that it will cancel Friday's mass service on Feb. 28. At the same time, Iran will restrict access to places of worship such as the Imam Reza Shrine in Mashhad and the Fatima Masumeh Shrine in Qom, requiring worshippers to wear face masks, carry their own hand sanitizer and show health information.

It is not an easy decision for a secular Iran. Friday prayers are an extremely important part of life for Muslims. Earlier, some clerics had said that reading the Koran could ward off the virus. Some clerics said that worshipping at the Holy Shrine could cure the disease. But scientists told the Iranian government that there was a high risk of an epidemic spreading on a large scale, so Friday prayers were canceled, this is an extremely difficult decision for Iran.

Even so, the measures taken by Iran and China's all-out Defense of the situation is still relatively lax, not to "seal off" the intention. President Rohani said Feb. 26, "the country has not decided to quarantine any city, people do not listen to the rumors envelope city, all living materials have adequate supplies. ". The mobilization of resources needed for the closure of the city, as well as the bearing capacity of the country's economy, are unbearable for Iran.

Just like the Great Flood, when you can't block it up, you can only choose to block it up. The Supreme Leader's Foreign Affairs Adviser and prominent Iranian pediatrician, Dr. Velayati, appeared on television in a white lab coat and told the public that "the new coronavirus is less lethal than the flu. ". "Most infected people don't need to go to the hospital, but can rest at home and take water and vitamin supplements, " said Vice Health Minister Khaleesi, who was in good spirits in the video he made.

There was no panic as the country tried to "cool down" the outbreak. But that's only part of the story, and much of it is religious, with one supermarket official explaining why he doesn't wear a mask: "It's all in God's hands. ".

The author observed locally that while the epidemic was spreading, the Iranian people did not take good protective measures. The number of people wearing masks on the streets was only about 10 percent. The traffic jam in Tehran was not eased because of the epidemic, most people go about their business as usual. More interestingly, due to the closure of schools, some students even went on a group holiday near the Caspian Sea in northern Iran, where the city also had confirmed cases. The matter led the Ministry of Health to call directly, "I didn't suspend you to go on a trip. Stay in your dorms. ".

Although most people appear to be in a stable mood, pharmacies are running out of face masks, alcohol and disinfectant. Iran, which has been under sanctions for a long time, is indeed unable to cope with the rise in the demand for medical care due to the large-scale outbreak of the epidemic.

Further isolated

Whether Iran's virus originated in China remains to be seen, but confirmed cases in many countries have been confirmed to have been "transported" through Iran.

On 20 February, the sixth confirmed case in British Columbia, Canada, was a woman in her 30s who had returned from Iran. The first reported case in Lebanon was a 45 year old Lebanese woman who returned from a trip to Qom on Tuesday. A 70-year-old Iranian tourist and his 64-year-old wife were among two more confirmed cases in the United Arab Emirates Tuesday. The author has counted the number of confirmed cases from Iran found in various countries, 43 from Kuwait, 2 from Lebanon, 4 from Iraq, 26 from Bahrain, 2 from Oman, 2 from the United Arab Emirates, 1 from Pakistan and 1 from Canada, another Chinese man was diagnosed after returning to China from Iran.

When Iran became the "drug source" in the Middle East, all countries urgently shut down air and land traffic with Iran. In addition to the countries from which the confirmed case of Iran was found, Turkey, Tajikistan and others also cut off ties with Iran, iran is almost an island. The Chinese who are still in Iran are horrified to find that direct flights between Iran and China have been cancelled due to the Chinese epidemic, and the return routes that had previously been diverted through cities such as Dubai, Moscow and Istanbul have also been blocked, there's no turning back.
